# Performance philosophy (Medora-S)

Medora-S must remain **lightweight**. Default choices should favor simplicity and predictable cost.

## Avoid (unless there is a strong, scoped reason)

- Heavy frontend frameworks or stacks that add large bundle/runtime cost
- **Excessive API calls** (chatty UIs, redundant refetches without need)
- **Complex joins on every request** — prefer targeted queries and bounded includes
- **Deep nested data fetching** — fetch what the screen needs; avoid N+1 and huge graphs per click
- **Real-time streaming infrastructure** (WebSockets, SSE fleets, etc.) as a default pattern

## Prefer

- **Simple REST APIs** — clear resources, standard verbs
- **Predictable database queries** — explicit selects, indexes in mind, avoid accidental full scans
- **Paginated list endpoints** (`limit` / `offset` or cursor where appropriate)
- **Efficient chart-summary aggregation** — dedicated summary endpoints or aggregated reads instead of many round-trips

## When proposing features

- Prefer fewer, well-shaped endpoints over many tiny ones.
- Prefer pagination for lists that can grow.
- Call out any deviation (e.g. “this adds polling or extra joins”) explicitly.
